{"timestamp": "2025-12-06 23:04:00.782821", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\n\nScope and goals\n- Detect anomalies in end-to-end connectivity/performance.\n- Localize faulty devices/segments.\n- Identify likely root cause(s) without proposing remediation.\n\nSummary of overall health\n- Control-plane: OSPF adjacencies are established and stable across core, distribution, and server access segments. All expected routes (10.<core>.<dist>.0/24 access subnets and 10.200.0.0/24 server farm) are present via OSPF on all routers queried.\n  - Example: server_access_router shows Full adjacency to core (eth7) and OSPF-learned routes to all access subnets; 10.200.0.0/24 is directly connected on br0.\n- Data-plane reachability: End-to-end pings from hosts to DNS, load balancer, and web servers succeed (0% loss). Backend servers on 20.200.0.0/24 are not reachable from hosts, which matches the design (backend isolation).\n  - Example: host_1_1_1_1 to backend_web_0 (20.200.0.2) returns “Destination Net Unreachable” via 10.1.1.1 — expected behavior by policy.\n- Name resolution: curl to webX.local and web99.local from hosts succeeds, indicating DNS is functional.\n- Load balancer to backends: Connectivity is good; pings succeed and iperf shows normal delivery to web_server_1 and reduced throughput to web_server_0 (see findings below).\n\nObserved anomalies and impact\n1) Elevated and variable latency to servers in 10.200.0.0/24 from hosts\n   - Host-to-server pings show occasional high RTTs (up to ~100+ ms), unusual for a local lab.\n   - Curl timing from hosts to individual front-end servers (web0–web3) shows intermittently high time-to-first-byte (TTFB), particularly when targeting web0.local, and sometimes web1/2, with total times ranging roughly 1.1–2.8 s.\n\n2) Strong asymmetry in traffic on server_access_router toward web_server_0\n   - server_access_router interface counters show disproportionately large TX volume on eth1 (the link to web_server_0) relative to other server links, suggesting a skew of traffic toward that server.\n\n3) Host interface DHCP lease durations are unusually short (36–60 seconds)\n   - Both host_1_1_1_1 and host_2_1_1_1 display dynamic DHCP leases with ~36–60s valid_lft. No immediate connectivity fault seen, but atypical and could contribute to periodic jitter due to frequent renewals.\n\nKey evidence\n- Traffic control on web_server_0 eth0:\n  - tc on web_server_0 shows qdisc netem with a 20ms delay and a TBF shaper at 1 Mbit/s on eth0:\n    - “qdisc netem 1: root … delay 20ms”\n    - “qdisc tbf 10: parent 1:1 rate 1Mbit burst 500Kb”\n  - This will:\n    - Introduce a fixed 20ms one-way delay on egress from web_server_0.\n    - Cap egress throughput from web_server_0 around 1 Mbit/s, directly affecting HTTP responses served from this host to clients.\n- Performance correlation:\n  - host -> web0.local: curl shows high TTFB (e.g., 1.22–1.53 s) and higher totals (2.3–2.75 s) compared to other servers.\n  - load_balancer -> web_server_0 iperf: ~9–12 Mbit/s measured; while the shaper is on egress from web_server_0, ACK pacing and the imposed delay can still limit effective throughput. By contrast, load_balancer -> web_server_1 iperf reaches ~30–35 Mbit/s.\n  - ICMP RTTs to 10.200.0.x from hosts show periodic spikes (20–124 ms), with the worst and most consistent elevation seen when the path involves web_server_0.\n- Routing/control-plane:\n  - All OSPF neighbors are Full; route tables across server_access_router, dist, and core routers contain the expected entries. No routing black holes or asymmetries observed.\n- Backend isolation:\n  - host_1_1_1_1 to 20.200.0.2 returns net unreachable via the default gateway; consistent with design that backends are not directly accessible from user subnets.\n\nLocalization\n- The problematic behavior is localized to web_server_0’s interface configuration (eth0). The presence of netem delay and TBF shaping uniquely on web_server_0 explains:\n  - Increased RTT and jitter observed when interacting with web0.local.\n  - Reduced application throughput and higher TTFB when clients are served by web_server_0.\n  - Disproportionate traffic forwarding on server_access_router eth1 (server_access_router -> web_server_0) during tests when that server is selected.\n- The core/distribution/server access routers appear healthy. OSPF adjacency and routing are correct, and other servers (web1–web3) do not exhibit the same systemic shaping-induced behavior.\n\nRoot cause assessment\n- Root cause: Artificial traffic shaping and delay applied on web_server_0 eth0 (qdisc netem 20ms + TBF 1 Mbit/s) causing:\n  - Elevated and variable end-to-end latency for flows sourced by web_server_0.\n  - Throughput reduction for HTTP responses from web_server_0 to clients, increasing TTFB and total transfer times.\n  - Collateral impact when the load balancer selects web_server_0 as a backend (clients see slower responses compared to other backends).\n- Secondary notes:\n  - Backend isolation (20.200.0.0/24) from hosts is as-designed and not a fault.\n  - Unusually short DHCP leases exist but did not cause observed losses; they are noted as atypical rather than causal for the HTTP performance symptoms.\n\nConclusion\n- The network control-plane (OSPF) and general reachability are healthy.\n- The dominant performance anomaly is due to intentional/accidental traffic control on web_server_0’s NIC, producing higher latency and lower throughput for that server and any client flows served by it.\n- No evidence of a routing protocol failure or general infrastructure fault; the issue is localized to web_server_0’s interface QoS configuration.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 28606, "output_tokens": 4766, "total_tokens": 33372, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 23040}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 3392}}}
